[2] Liberia: Ebola transmission tracked to one source (in Sierra Leone)
Date: Wed 9 Dec 2015
Source: Medical News Today (MNT) [edited]
http://www.medicalnewstoday.com/articles/303832.php


According to Cell Host & Microbe [journal], it is likely most cases in the latest reemergence of Ebola virus disease (EVD) in Liberia originated from just one source.

Contact tracing has shown at least 3 potential introductions of the Ebola virus disease (EVD) to Liberia from Sierra Leone around the start of the 2nd reemergence of Liberian cases. Although EVD spread to Liberia several times from neighboring countries early during the outbreak, it now appears that most Liberian cases came from a single introduction of the virus, in late May or early June 2014, around the start of the 2nd wave of Liberian cases. EVD then spread rapidly through the country, refueling the ongoing outbreak in Guinea.

According to Jason Ladner of the US Army Medical Research Institute of Infectious Diseases (USAMRIID), "The widespread movement of the Ebola virus [EBOV] within Liberia, due to a high rate of migration in the country, is likely to have played an important role in the magnitude and longevity of the Liberian portion of the Ebola outbreak. Regular migration of infected individuals complicates surveillance and isolation efforts, which are critical for controlling Ebola outbreaks."

The study also reported that 140 EBOV genomes from Liberian patients were sequenced and analyzed with 782 other sequences, that reintroductions from Liberia helped sustain the Guinea and Mali outbreaks, and that there was limited evidence of incremental Ebola virus adaptation to the human host.

[Byline: Yvette Brazier]

Reference
---------
Ladner JT, Wiley MR, Mate S, et al: Evolution and Spread of Ebola Virus in Liberia, 2014-2015. Cell Host & Microbe 2015; 18(6): 659-69; available at http://www.cell.com/cell-host-microbe/fulltext/S1931-3128(15)00462-X

