[4] Prevention, technology, funding
Prevention
----------
9 Dec 2015 New Zealand: NZ Ebola screening to be scaled back
http://www.nzherald.co.nz/health/news/article.cfm?c_id=204&objectid=11558499
[With Sierra Leone recently declared free of Ebola virus disease (EVD) transmission, New Zealand`s efforts at border screening are being scaled back.]

7 Dec 2015 Sierra Leone: Ebola -- Sierra Lone cleared to host matches
http://thenationonlineng.net/ebola-sierra-lone-cleared-to-host-matches/
[In August 2014, the Confederation of African Football (CAF) banned Sierra Leone from hosting matches following the recommendations of the World Health Organization (WHO). However, in a letter dated 6 Dec 2015, CAF informed Sierra Leone the ban has been lifted following the end of Ebola virus disease (EVD) transmission the country.

9 Dec 2015 Liberia: They helped erase Ebola -- now Liberia is erasing them.
http://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/10/world/africa/they-helped-erase-ebola-in-liberia-now-liberia-is-erasing-them.html
[Psychological trauma in crematorium workers]

Non-governmental organizations
------------------------------
7 Dec 2015 WHO: Disease specialists identify post-Ebola threats
http://www.nature.com/news/disease-specialists-identify-post-ebola-threats-1.18952
Scientists and doctors are meeting today (8 Dec 2015) and tomorrow (9 Dec 2015) in Geneva, Switzerland to discuss which infectious disease may start the next pandemic.

The top candidates so far are:
- other Ebola virus disease (EVD) species or Marburg virus disease (MARV);
- Middle East respiratory syndrome (MERS) and related viruses;
- Influenza;
- Nipah (NiV) virus disease and Hendra (HeV) virus disease;
- the unknown.

6 Dec 2015 West Africa: Curbing Ebola -- Liberia, Sierra Leone, Guinea must invest in sensitization
http://www.frontpageafricaonline.com/index.php/op-ed/editorial/6897-curbing-ebola-liberia-sierra-leone-guinea-must-invest-in-sensitization
[Many survivors lack counselling and more importantly, are facing various health problems, signaling that if nothing is done to address this, this batch of survivors could essentially be the reservoir that sparks the next major outbreak. It is important now, more than ever before that governments in these 3 countries understand how the disease continues to affect the survivors if they are serious about eradicating the virus for good. Failure to take precautions now and invest in sensitization and communications programs that will aid the full recovery of survivors (could have serious consequences).]

Technology
----------
7 Dec 2015: Ultraviolet LEDs could be used to fight disease
http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/ultraviolet-leds-could-be-used-fight-disease-1532134
["The ultraviolet light-emitting diode (UV LED) could serve as great help in medical field as it has potential to eradicate infectious diseases such as Ebola." Marketing hype -- check the product on its website. This is very expensive and completely impractical. It is a pulsed UV xenon lamp on top of a waist-high wheeled trolley, all furniture must be removed, the operator must exit the room while it is operating, wall fixtures like handbasins will cast shadows into which the UV cannot reach. A reduction of 3 logs in virus titer means only a 1000-fold reduction, which is insignificant because a drop of dried blood on a surface could contains millions of infectious virus particles.

Funding
-------
7 Dec 2015 West Africa: Ebola investment boosts neglected-disease research
http://www.nature.com/news/ebola-investment-boosts-neglected-disease-research-1.18975
[Funding for work on neglected diseases increased by USD 150 million in 2014, to USD 3.37 billion. However, investments made to address the Ebola virus disease (EVD) epidemic -- which started in West Africa in 2014 -- were entirely responsible for the increase. While money from industry for Ebola research rose, money from public funding decreased.]

7 Dec 2015 Gambia: Ebola Poses Significant Threat to Economic Growth -- WAMZ DG http://allafrica.com/stories/201512072030.html
[According to the Director General of the West Africa Monetary Zone (WAMZ), Abawaku Englama, while speaking at the 7th Edition of WAMZ Trade Ministers forum in Gambia, the outbreak of Ebola virus disease (EVD) presents a significant threat to agriculture, mining, construction, manufacturing, tourism, and transportation. It has also negatively impacted some of the major developments of the Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS) activities in 2014 in the member countries.

[Compiled by: Celeste Whitlow <whitlow.celeste@gmail.com>]

